\section{Coupled-channel CDD analysis II: including the widths of $\Sigma_c$}
\label{sec.211015.1}


Now we estimate the effects of taking into account the small but finite widths of the $\Sigma_c$ baryons to evaluate $t(s)$
from Eq.~\eqref{201015.1}. As indicated above we take for the widths of $\Sigma_c^{++}$ and $\Sigma_c^0$ the central values
 provided by the updated PDG \cite{150915.1.pdg}, $\Gamma_{\Sigma_c^{++}}=1.89$~MeV and $\Gamma_{\Sigma_c^0}=1.83$~MeV.   For
the $\Sigma_c^+$ we use in the following the value $\Gamma_{\Sigma_c^+}=1.8$~MeV, because it is naturally expected  that its decay width
 should be saturated also by the strong decay to $\Lambda_c^+\pi$~\cite{150915.1.pdg} and then its value should be very close to the widths
 of its other isospin multiplet companions. Note also that the decay channel $\Lambda_c^+\pi$ has a much lighter threshold than the $\Sigma_c$ mass,
so that there is  plenty of phase space available and then the width should be quite insensitive to
small changes in the masses of the decaying particles.


